# Linux Commands for DevOps

These are some of the most commonly used Linux commands during DevOps work. Every command below includes what it does and when we use it.


# 1. User and System Information Commands

## whoami

Shows the currently logged-in user.

whoami


Example Output:

ec2-user


## hostnamectl set-hostname aws

Changes the system hostname to `aws`.

hostnamectl set-hostname aws

exec bash

To verify:

hostname


## timedatectl

Displays current date, time, timezone, and NTP status.

timedatectl


Example Output:

Local time: Wed 2026-04-15 10:30:00 IST
Time zone: Asia/Kolkata


## timedatectl set-timezone Asia/Kolkata

Changes the system timezone to Indian Standard Time.

sudo timedatectl set-timezone Asia/Kolkata


To verify:

timedatectl


# 2. Hardware Information Commands

## cat /proc/cpuinfo

Displays detailed CPU information.

cat /proc/cpuinfo


Useful to know:

* Processor model
* Number of cores
* CPU speed


## lscpu

Displays CPU architecture and summary information in a cleaner format.

lscpu


## cat /proc/meminfo

Displays detailed RAM and memory information.

cat /proc/meminfo


## free

Displays available and used memory.

free


## free -m

Displays memory information in MB.

free -m


## fdisk -l

Displays all disk partitions available in the system.

sudo fdisk -l

## df -h

Displays disk usage in human-readable format.

df -h


Example:


Filesystem      Size  Used Avail Use% Mounted on
/dev/xvda1       20G   10G    9G  53% /

# 3. File Commands

## touch file1

Creates an empty file named `file1`.

touch file1


## ls

Lists files and folders in the current directory.

ls


## ll

Displays files in long listing format.

ll


If `ll` does not work in your system, use:

ls -l

## touch a b c

Creates multiple files at the same time.

touch a b c


## touch file{1..7}

Creates files from `file1` to `file7`.

touch file{1..7}


Files created:

file1 file2 file3 file4 file5 file6 file7

## rm file1

Deletes the file `file1`.

rm file1


If the file is write-protected, Linux asks for confirmation before deleting.


## rm file1 file2 file3

Deletes multiple files.

rm file1 file2 file3

## rm -f file{1..5}

Force deletes files from `file1` to `file5` without asking for confirmation.

rm -f file{1..5}


## rm -f *

Deletes all files in the current directory without confirmation.

rm -f *


Be very careful while using this command.

## rm -f a*

Deletes all files whose names start with `a`.

rm -f a*


Example:

abc.txt
apple.txt
aws.log


All of the above files will be deleted.

# 4. Folder Commands

## mkdir aws

Creates a folder named `aws`.

mkdir aws


## mkdir folder1 folder2

Creates multiple folders.

mkdir folder1 folder2


## mkdir devops{1..5}

Creates multiple folders using brace expansion.

mkdir devops{1..5}

Folders created:

devops1 devops2 devops3 devops4 devops5


## rmdir aws

Deletes an empty folder.

rmdir aws

`rmdir` works only if the folder is empty.


## rmdir folder1 folder2

Deletes multiple empty folders.

rmdir folder1 folder2


## rmdir devops{1..5}

Deletes multiple empty folders.

rmdir devops{1..5}


## rmdir *

Deletes all empty folders in the current directory.

rmdir *


## rm -rf *

Deletes all files and folders recursively without confirmation.

rm -rf *


⚠️ Dangerous command. Never run this command in important directories.


# 5. Navigation Commands

## pwd

Shows the present working directory.

pwd


## cd foldername

Moves into a folder.

cd folder1


## cd -

Moves back to the previous directory.

cd -


## cd ..

Moves one level up.

cd ..


## cd ../..

Moves two levels up.

cd ../..


## cd ../../..

Moves three levels up.

cd ../../..


# 6. Nested Folder and File Creation

## mkdir -p folder1/folder2

Creates parent and child folders together.

mkdir -p folder1/folder2


> The ommand `mkdir folder1/folder2` may fail if `folder1` does not exist. Using `-p` is the correct approach.



## ls folder1

Displays the contents inside `folder1`.

ls folder1

## touch folder1/aws

Creates a file named `aws` inside `folder1`.

touch folder1/aws


## mkdir -p f1/f2/f3

Creates multiple nested folders in a single command.

mkdir -p f1/f2/f3


# 7. Advanced Listing Commands

## ll -t

Displays files sorted by latest modified time.

ll -t


## ll -r

Displays files in reverse order.

ll -r


## ll -a

Displays all files including hidden files.

ll -a

## touch .aws

Creates a hidden file named `.aws`.

touch .aws

## ll -ltr

Displays files in long listing format, sorted by oldest modified time.

ll -ltr


## ll -rtl

Displays files in reverse order with long listing.

ll -rtl

## ll --color=auto

Displays files with colored output.

ll --color=auto

# 8. File Content Commands

## cat aws

Displays the content of the file `aws`.

cat aws


## cat > aws

Creates a file and allows you to enter content.

cat > aws

Example:

cat > aws
Hello DevOps
Welcome to Linux

After typing the content, press:

Ctrl + D


to save and exit.


## cat >> aws

Appends new content to an existing file.

cat >> aws

Example:

cat >> aws
This line will be added to the existing file.


Then press:

Ctrl + D


# Important Notes

* `rm -rf *` is a dangerous command. Always check the current directory using `pwd` before using it.
* `rmdir` works only for empty folders.
* Hidden files start with `.` (dot).
* `ll` is usually an alias for `ls -l`.
* Use `sudo` when permission is required.
* Always verify before deleting important files or folders.



